WEBVTT

00:17.843 --> 00:18.757
[Claire] Previously...

00:18.888 --> 00:21.021
[Richard]
We've come to arrest her

00:21.108 --> 00:22.718
for the murder
of Malva Christie.

00:22.848 --> 00:23.545
[Tom] Let them both be taken,
if you will.

00:23.675 --> 00:24.676
I will travel with them.

00:24.763 --> 00:25.851
[person] Hang her!

00:25.982 --> 00:27.201
[dramatic music plays]

00:27.331 --> 00:28.941
This isn't justice!

00:29.072 --> 00:30.552
I want to spend my time
with you and Jemmy,

00:30.682 --> 00:31.770
just the three of us.

00:31.857 --> 00:33.859
Well, the four of us.

00:33.946 --> 00:35.644
[Roger] Really?

00:35.774 --> 00:37.646
[men grunting]

00:37.776 --> 00:39.952
-Jamie!
-Claire!

00:40.083 --> 00:41.606
Where are you taking Jamie?

00:41.693 --> 00:43.217
That's none of your concern.

00:43.347 --> 00:45.349
What if I want to make
the preaching official?

00:45.436 --> 00:47.743
I heard there's a Presbytery
in Edenton.

00:47.873 --> 00:50.398
We'll start packing tomorrow
and leave as soon as we can.

00:50.528 --> 00:51.660
Your husband is alive.

00:51.790 --> 00:53.749
Trust in God.

00:53.879 --> 00:56.099
He will deliver the righteous
out of danger.

00:56.230 --> 00:57.883
You think I'm righteous?

00:57.970 --> 00:59.189
[Tom] I will not leave town.

00:59.363 --> 01:02.062
♪ ♪

01:05.500 --> 01:08.285
[ominous music plays]

01:08.372 --> 01:11.114
♪ ♪

01:21.603 --> 01:23.648
[exhales shakily]

01:23.779 --> 01:26.086
[indistinct whispering]

01:26.260 --> 01:29.001
♪ ♪

01:37.532 --> 01:40.317
[hyperventilating]

01:40.491 --> 01:41.449
♪ ♪

01:41.579 --> 01:44.365
[sobbing]

01:46.280 --> 01:48.108
[people gasping]

01:48.195 --> 01:50.936
[tense music plays]

01:51.110 --> 01:53.852
♪ ♪

01:55.898 --> 01:57.204
[Ian] Uncle Jamie?

01:57.378 --> 02:00.294
♪ ♪

02:00.424 --> 02:03.166
Uncle Jamie?

02:03.297 --> 02:05.560
[Jamie] I canna let
my darkest fears cripple me.

02:05.690 --> 02:08.693
Blood of my blood,
bone of my bone,

02:08.824 --> 02:10.869
I gave ye my spirit
till our life shall be done.

02:11.000 --> 02:14.221
And that's why I ken
ye're alive still.

02:14.308 --> 02:16.310
I'd feel it if you were gone.

02:16.397 --> 02:18.181
You live.

02:18.312 --> 02:20.836
I ken it in my bones,
and I will find you.

02:21.837 --> 02:23.752
[Ian] Horses are watered,
Uncle Jamie.

02:23.882 --> 02:26.102
John Quincy and the Cherokee
are away back to the Ridge

02:26.189 --> 02:29.279
to see that all is well,
just as ye asked.

02:29.410 --> 02:31.325
And ye're right.

02:31.454 --> 02:32.848
We'll attract less attention
in town this way.

02:34.545 --> 02:35.546
Uncle Jamie?

02:37.069 --> 02:38.680
Let's go get my wife.

02:38.810 --> 02:41.552
[dramatic music plays]

02:41.726 --> 02:44.468
♪ ♪

02:51.692 --> 02:54.086
[singer] ♪ Sing me a song ♪

02:54.261 --> 02:57.567
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

02:57.655 --> 03:00.354
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

03:00.528 --> 03:03.313
♪ Be I? ♪

03:03.487 --> 03:06.055
♪ Merry of soul ♪

03:06.229 --> 03:09.101
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

03:09.276 --> 03:11.452
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:11.626 --> 03:14.629
♪ To Skye ♪

03:14.803 --> 03:17.414
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

03:17.588 --> 03:20.329
♪ Islands and seas ♪

03:20.417 --> 03:26.031
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

03:26.206 --> 03:28.860
♪ All that was good ♪

03:28.947 --> 03:31.689
♪ All that was fair ♪

03:31.863 --> 03:33.952
♪ All that was me ♪

03:34.126 --> 03:36.999
♪ Is gone ♪

03:37.173 --> 03:39.567
♪ Sing me a song ♪

03:39.741 --> 03:42.700
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

03:42.874 --> 03:45.747
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

03:45.834 --> 03:48.271
♪ Be I? ♪

03:48.445 --> 03:50.795
♪ Merry of soul ♪

03:50.969 --> 03:53.885
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

03:53.972 --> 03:58.238
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:58.325 --> 04:04.069
♪ To Skye ♪

04:05.506 --> 04:08.291
[dramatic music plays]

04:08.465 --> 04:11.251
♪ ♪

04:13.383 --> 04:17.257
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:17.430 --> 04:21.913
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

04:22.087 --> 04:26.875
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:27.049 --> 04:28.877
♪ Be I? ♪

04:30.444 --> 04:33.229
[person coughing]

04:34.970 --> 04:37.799
[chain clinking]

04:46.808 --> 04:49.114
Sorry.
I- I didn't mean to disturb you.

04:49.201 --> 04:50.290
Think nothing of it.

04:51.726 --> 04:53.118
Did he give you money?

04:53.249 --> 04:55.599
Yes, a bit.

04:55.730 --> 04:57.034
Well, call the old bizzom

04:57.122 --> 04:58.298
and send for some Holland,
why don't you?

04:58.907 --> 04:59.821
Who?

05:00.952 --> 05:01.953
Mrs. Tolliver?

05:02.911 --> 05:04.260
Mrs. Tolliver!

05:04.391 --> 05:06.567
[Mrs. Tolliver]
Really, Mrs. Ferguson,

05:06.697 --> 05:09.178
you are
the most dreadful nuisance.

05:09.309 --> 05:11.049
I was just coming
to pay my respects

05:11.136 --> 05:13.530
to Mrs. Fraser in any case.

05:13.617 --> 05:16.490
Mrs. Fraser,
I am Mrs. Tolliver.

05:16.577 --> 05:18.579
-Mrs. Tolliver.
-I'm to see to your welfare

05:18.709 --> 05:20.363
and acquaint you
with our custom.

05:20.929 --> 05:23.584
You will receive
one meal each day,

05:23.671 --> 05:25.847
unless you wish to send
to the ordinary for more,

05:25.934 --> 05:27.544
at your own expense.

05:27.675 --> 05:30.504
I will bring a basin
for washing once a day,

05:30.591 --> 05:32.506
and you will carry
your own slops.

05:32.636 --> 05:35.030
Stuff your custom, Maisie.
She has some money.

05:35.159 --> 05:37.075
Fetch us a bottle of geneva.
There's a good girl.

05:37.206 --> 05:38.729
Then if you must,
you can tell her what's what.

05:42.080 --> 05:43.038
A shilling, then.

05:45.475 --> 05:47.738
You've missed supper,
but as you've just come,

05:47.825 --> 05:50.654
I'll make an allowance
and bring you something.

05:51.655 --> 05:53.353
Thank you. I'm famished.

05:53.440 --> 05:55.355
None for me, thanks.

05:55.485 --> 05:57.269
Just the gin.

05:57.400 --> 06:00.272
Please, could you get a word
to my family?

06:00.403 --> 06:02.057
[Mrs. Tolliver]
That I cannot do. I'm sorry.

06:02.187 --> 06:04.625
[Sadie] Fraser, she said.

06:04.712 --> 06:05.800
You aren't the, uh...

06:05.930 --> 06:07.367
[whispering] ...murderess?

06:07.497 --> 06:09.194
I don't want to talk about it.

06:09.325 --> 06:10.718
[Sadie] As you like.

06:10.805 --> 06:12.589
Welcome to your new home,
then.

06:12.720 --> 06:14.199
Used to be a slaughterhouse,
they say.

06:15.897 --> 06:17.377
Seems about right.

06:17.507 --> 06:19.466
[Sadie] It's grand here, it is.

06:19.596 --> 06:21.903
Sit, sit.

06:22.033 --> 06:23.861
You must be bone tired.

06:23.992 --> 06:25.950
I'm Sadie, by the bye.

06:28.082 --> 06:29.824
-Claire.
-[Sadie] You, uh...

06:29.911 --> 06:32.261
any good at cards, Claire?

06:32.392 --> 06:33.480
Know a game called Brag?

06:34.916 --> 06:36.831
Let me guess.

06:36.961 --> 06:38.310
You're in here
for cheating at cards.

06:38.441 --> 06:39.834
Cheat?

06:39.921 --> 06:41.401
Sadie Ferguson?

06:41.531 --> 06:42.489
Not a bit of it.

06:44.186 --> 06:45.100
Forgery.

06:49.887 --> 06:52.542
All right then,
but not for money.

06:52.629 --> 06:54.501
Hmm.

06:54.631 --> 06:56.764
We'll play for beans then,
shall we?

06:57.808 --> 06:59.375
[Claire] How long have you
been in here?

06:59.506 --> 07:01.725
[Sadie] A month, almost.

07:01.812 --> 07:03.727
29 days, by last count.

07:04.249 --> 07:05.686
You haven't had a trial yet?

07:05.816 --> 07:08.297
[Sadie] No, praise God.

07:08.384 --> 07:10.734
[Margit] Hasn't been anybody
tried in the last two months.

07:10.865 --> 07:13.302
Maisie says
the court's shut down,

07:13.433 --> 07:14.738
all the justices gone
into hiding.

07:14.869 --> 07:16.610
[Claire] So here too, then?

07:16.697 --> 07:18.307
[Sadie] Well, I wouldn't be
in a hurry, dearie.

07:18.438 --> 07:20.875
If they've not tried you,
they can't hang you.

07:21.005 --> 07:22.703
-I am innocent.
-[Sadie] 'Course you are.

07:22.832 --> 07:24.356
You stick to it.

07:24.487 --> 07:25.619
Don't let 'em bully-whack you
into admitting

07:25.749 --> 07:26.358
the least little thing.

07:28.752 --> 07:29.623
I won't.

07:31.799 --> 07:33.670
But I don't want to languish
here in jail either.

07:34.279 --> 07:35.498
If the courts aren't open
now--

07:35.629 --> 07:38.632
One who should worry about
hanging's the sheriff.

07:38.762 --> 07:41.243
What I hear,
a mob's liable to come here

07:41.373 --> 07:42.940
and string him up
if he don't look sharp.

07:43.071 --> 07:44.028
[Margit] There's unrest
in the streets,

07:44.159 --> 07:45.247
if you hadn't noticed.

07:45.377 --> 07:46.814
The rebels have made it hell

07:46.944 --> 07:49.164
for any loyal subject.

07:49.294 --> 07:52.210
[tense music plays]

07:52.297 --> 07:54.343
What ails you, Mistress?

07:55.082 --> 07:56.780
[Claire] I could not tell her
what it was.

07:56.911 --> 07:58.347
Could not say that I knew

07:58.478 --> 08:00.305
just how long
this war would last,

08:00.436 --> 08:02.003
that the courts
would likely remain closed

08:02.133 --> 08:03.570
for years to come,

08:03.700 --> 08:05.789
and we would languish here
without rescue.

08:05.920 --> 08:08.662
[dramatic music plays]

08:08.836 --> 08:11.578
♪ ♪

08:19.890 --> 08:22.327
It feels like I'm throwing you
to the wolves.

08:22.457 --> 08:25.156
I think they're more commonly
known as wives.

08:25.287 --> 08:26.462
Same difference.

08:26.593 --> 08:29.857
[birds chirping]

08:29.987 --> 08:32.467
Are you gonna be okay
with Reverend McMillan?

08:33.337 --> 08:34.905
Surely I can handle ministering
to a few soldiers.

08:36.690 --> 08:39.388
I'm a veteran myself now,
sort of.

08:40.780 --> 08:41.607
And I'm tough.

08:43.174 --> 08:45.394
I had my wayward youth.

08:45.481 --> 08:47.788
Smoking, drinking beer.

08:47.918 --> 08:49.311
Wow.

08:49.441 --> 08:51.052
Stealing sweeties
from the post office.

08:51.182 --> 08:52.836
Quite the wee criminal
for a while.

08:54.708 --> 08:56.448
The terror of Inverness.

08:56.579 --> 08:58.015
[Roger] Son of a preacher man.

08:58.973 --> 09:00.148
Still,
I think Reverend McMillan wants

09:00.278 --> 09:01.976
to test my mettle,

09:02.106 --> 09:03.543
make sure I'm not too focused

09:03.673 --> 09:05.719
on the lofty, intellectual
parts of my studies.

09:08.156 --> 09:10.071
What is it?

09:10.201 --> 09:11.725
There's something written
all over your face.

09:13.422 --> 09:15.250
What do you even say
to a preacher?

09:15.337 --> 09:16.947
"Break a leg"
doesn't seem right.

09:18.383 --> 09:19.384
-"God luck"?
-[snorts]

09:20.298 --> 09:22.344
[both laughing]

09:22.474 --> 09:24.607
Good day to you both.

09:24.694 --> 09:26.391
Thank you, Mistress MacKenzie,

09:26.522 --> 09:28.872
for your willingness to assist
with the almsgiving,

09:29.003 --> 09:31.005
especially since you'll only be
with us for a few weeks.

09:32.441 --> 09:34.443
Of course.

09:34.574 --> 09:36.532
Are you ready, Mr. MacKenzie?

09:36.619 --> 09:38.142
The soldiers
we'll encounter today

09:38.273 --> 09:40.144
are mustering to go north.

09:41.581 --> 09:45.367
Now, it's not for us to judge

09:45.497 --> 09:48.762
which side they have chosen
to fight for,

09:48.892 --> 09:52.200
but know that they'll be
in need of much prayer

09:52.330 --> 09:53.549
and supplication.

09:56.247 --> 09:59.033
[militaristic music plays]

09:59.120 --> 10:01.862
♪ ♪

10:22.883 --> 10:25.537
[indistinct chatter]

10:27.452 --> 10:29.324
Good day, young one.

10:29.454 --> 10:31.152
Could we offer you some comfort

10:31.282 --> 10:33.241
through the word of God?

10:33.371 --> 10:37.419
The future Reverend MacKenzie
was at the Battle of Alamance.

10:37.549 --> 10:39.769
Doin' what, exactly?

10:39.900 --> 10:40.901
Carryin' the white flag
of surrender?

10:44.078 --> 10:46.254
Bible verse ain't gonna
help us.

10:46.341 --> 10:49.126
Knowin' how to wield a knife,
use our fists, maybe.

10:49.257 --> 10:50.737
There's nothin'
in your holy book about that.

10:53.957 --> 10:56.351
What advice can these
devil-dodgers give us, eh?

10:56.438 --> 10:59.223
[laughter]

11:05.099 --> 11:07.405
"Float like a butterfly.

11:07.492 --> 11:08.450
Sting like a bee."

11:10.495 --> 11:13.411
And God will surely go
with thee.

11:13.542 --> 11:14.499
Ali.

11:14.586 --> 11:17.415
[tense music plays]

11:17.502 --> 11:20.331
♪ ♪

11:27.425 --> 11:29.166
What did you just say?

11:29.297 --> 11:30.298
Muhammad Ali.

11:32.256 --> 11:34.171
You're a traveler,
aren't you, like me?

11:35.520 --> 11:36.652
You gotta help me.

11:38.306 --> 11:39.699
Who are you?

11:39.829 --> 11:40.525
Wendigo Donner.

11:42.353 --> 11:43.746
You were one
of Lionel Brown's men.

11:43.877 --> 11:45.008
Claire Fraser told me--

11:45.139 --> 11:45.748
I didn't do nothing to her,
okay?

11:45.835 --> 11:47.663
I swear.

11:47.750 --> 11:48.490
I was gonna help her get away.

11:48.620 --> 11:49.360
Didn't she tell you?

11:51.841 --> 11:53.495
Why would I hurt her?

11:53.625 --> 11:54.714
She's like us, isn't she?

11:58.587 --> 12:00.763
I was conscripted from jail,
but I'm not a thief, okay?

12:00.894 --> 12:03.897
I just needed a gemstone
to get back to my own time.

12:04.027 --> 12:05.376
I've still got it,
but I'm stuck here.

12:07.509 --> 12:09.119
I came back to help
the Indian Nations, but...

12:10.599 --> 12:11.687
Well, Claire did tell me that.

12:13.515 --> 12:14.864
The plan just got
all screwed up.

12:16.910 --> 12:19.303
Five of us made it
to the stones at Ocracoke,

12:19.434 --> 12:20.827
but we got split up
when we went through.

12:20.957 --> 12:22.306
I don't know what happened.

12:22.393 --> 12:23.307
I never saw them again.

12:25.919 --> 12:27.921
I never even made it
to where I was supposed to go.

12:29.574 --> 12:30.837
Look,
I don't wanna hurt anybody.

12:33.013 --> 12:34.405
I just wanna go home.

12:34.536 --> 12:36.407
[somber music plays]

12:36.538 --> 12:37.626
You get that, right?

12:37.800 --> 12:40.629
♪ ♪

12:40.760 --> 12:43.937
Please... help me.

12:44.111 --> 12:46.896
♪ ♪

12:57.080 --> 13:00.301
[Mrs. Tolliver snoring softly]

13:01.171 --> 13:04.174
Sun's barely up,
and look at the state of Tolly,

13:04.305 --> 13:07.264
while we're here slaving away
at the arse-crack of dawn.

13:09.527 --> 13:12.052
Well, she's breathing fine,

13:12.182 --> 13:14.141
though a glass of water
wouldn't hurt.

13:15.055 --> 13:16.404
I doubt she'd drink it
if there's no gin in it.

13:16.534 --> 13:17.448
[Tate] Open it.

13:17.579 --> 13:19.320
[gate clanking, creaking]

13:19.450 --> 13:21.278
Ye gods and little fishes.
Here we are, Margit.

13:21.409 --> 13:22.453
Who's this now?

13:22.584 --> 13:24.891
[dramatic music plays]

13:25.065 --> 13:26.066
♪ ♪

13:26.196 --> 13:27.110
Which is the healer?

13:27.284 --> 13:29.373
♪ ♪

13:29.460 --> 13:30.592
That would be me.

13:32.289 --> 13:33.421
What is she charged with?

13:33.551 --> 13:35.162
Well, one of 'em's a forger,

13:35.292 --> 13:36.163
a few of them are thieves,

13:36.293 --> 13:37.773
and one of them's a murderess.

13:37.904 --> 13:39.906
Fletcher, Ferguson--
somethin' like that.

13:39.993 --> 13:42.169
But as to which one
being which...

13:42.299 --> 13:44.258
You mean to say you don't know?

13:44.345 --> 13:46.521
I'm paid to guard 'em,
not hobnob with 'em.

13:46.651 --> 13:48.349
-I'm the murderess.
-[Claire whispering] Sadie.

13:49.829 --> 13:50.960
Very well.

13:51.091 --> 13:51.831
Come with me.

13:54.442 --> 13:56.748
Well, where are we going?

13:56.879 --> 13:58.533
I'm afraid
we're in a hurry, madam.

13:58.707 --> 14:00.404
♪ ♪

14:00.535 --> 14:03.059
[gate clanking, creaking]

14:03.190 --> 14:05.845
[prisoners whispering]

14:30.695 --> 14:32.175
[Jamie] Mr. Christie!

14:32.306 --> 14:33.785
I'm glad to see
ye kept yer word.

14:33.915 --> 14:35.048
-Where is Claire?
-She's gone.

14:36.658 --> 14:38.312
You were supposed
to keep watch!

14:38.442 --> 14:40.444
The guards wouldn't allow me
to stand out here all night.

14:40.575 --> 14:42.664
When I came back this morning,
it was already too late.

14:42.794 --> 14:44.665
I did everything in my power.

14:44.796 --> 14:46.537
The sheriff assured me
they'd treat her with dignity.

14:47.974 --> 14:49.323
[sighs]

14:49.714 --> 14:51.629
[gate clanking, creaking]

14:56.896 --> 14:59.246
They're saying
that Auntie Claire was taken.

14:59.376 --> 15:00.725
Was it that bastard, Brown?

15:00.856 --> 15:02.858
No, no, it was soldiers
looking for a healer.

15:04.642 --> 15:06.340
[Jamie] Where was she taken?

15:06.470 --> 15:07.428
[Ian] They couldna tell me.

15:08.864 --> 15:10.605
Could not or would not?

15:10.735 --> 15:12.912
Got any drink, have you, sir?

15:13.042 --> 15:14.522
Or a few bob to pay for some?

15:14.609 --> 15:16.306
[coughs]

15:16.437 --> 15:18.439
Drop of something
for my poor old throat.

15:27.839 --> 15:28.884
Tell me what you know.

15:31.060 --> 15:32.453
A shilling more
and we'll make it

15:32.583 --> 15:33.976
a wee dram or two instead,
shall we?

15:34.934 --> 15:36.065
Nice lady.

15:36.196 --> 15:38.067
Did my best to help her.

15:38.981 --> 15:41.114
If anything, you probably ought
to be thanking me.

15:41.244 --> 15:43.290
If you truly want to help,

15:43.420 --> 15:45.118
then tell me
what you know, please.

15:45.248 --> 15:47.511
She told 'em your wife
was a forger

15:47.598 --> 15:50.165
and tried to claim
the murder charge for herself.

15:50.297 --> 15:52.995
Oh, no pardon possible
for forgery.

15:53.126 --> 15:54.649
Capital crime.

15:54.779 --> 15:57.478
But as for murder,

15:57.608 --> 16:00.307
she probably thinks
she can plead the Good Book,

16:00.437 --> 16:02.178
repent for her sins,
and get off scot-free.

16:02.309 --> 16:03.658
[Sadie] Don't be daft.

16:03.788 --> 16:04.920
You're living in fairy world

16:05.051 --> 16:06.139
if you think
I'd get away with that.

16:06.269 --> 16:07.531
I was trying to help her.

16:07.662 --> 16:09.577
Enough.

16:09.707 --> 16:11.144
You'd better thank the Lord
that that guard is watching.

16:11.274 --> 16:13.233
Now tell me!
Where did they take my wife?

16:13.363 --> 16:14.538
How the bleedin' hell
should I know?

16:14.669 --> 16:16.584
It's Tolly you want to ask.

16:16.714 --> 16:18.542
Mrs. Tolliver's
the sheriff's wife.

16:18.673 --> 16:20.327
[Margit laughs]

16:20.457 --> 16:22.372
She was as drunk as a lord
when those men came.

16:22.459 --> 16:24.548
I'm not even sure both
of 'em were soldiers as such.

16:24.679 --> 16:25.680
What did they look like,
these men?

16:26.637 --> 16:27.987
How would I know?

16:28.117 --> 16:28.900
They all look the same to me.

16:31.120 --> 16:32.600
[gate clanking]

16:32.730 --> 16:33.862
[Mrs. Tolliver]
What's going on here?

16:33.993 --> 16:35.429
Are you Mrs. Tolliver?

16:35.516 --> 16:37.648
I'm James Fraser.

16:37.779 --> 16:39.955
I demand to know
where my wife was taken.

16:41.000 --> 16:43.393
All I know is she was taken
on my husband's orders.

16:43.480 --> 16:45.221
A matter of duty to the Crown.

16:45.352 --> 16:46.396
And where is he, your husband?

16:46.527 --> 16:48.398
[scoffs]

16:48.529 --> 16:51.010
Do you think I'm privy
to such information,

16:51.140 --> 16:52.881
merely his wife?

16:54.448 --> 16:56.580
He'd gone to quell some unrest,

16:56.711 --> 16:58.191
rebels passing through

16:58.321 --> 17:00.845
on their way
to take Fort Johnston.

17:00.976 --> 17:04.806
He's likely drinking
his own sorrows away by now.

17:04.935 --> 17:06.155
Please go!

17:06.286 --> 17:08.983
[dramatic music plays]

17:09.157 --> 17:11.943
♪ ♪

17:32.094 --> 17:33.791
[knocking]

17:33.922 --> 17:35.097
[Mrs. Martin] Come in.

17:35.228 --> 17:37.012
[door clicking, creaking]

17:40.581 --> 17:41.886
Who the devil is this?

17:42.017 --> 17:44.498
Healer, ma'am. Midwife.

17:44.585 --> 17:46.108
A Mistress Fraser.

17:46.239 --> 17:48.110
I'm told there's not
a single midwife to be found

17:48.241 --> 17:49.894
in the entire county.

17:50.025 --> 17:51.374
Where did you find her?

17:51.505 --> 17:53.028
The workhouse
or the local jail?

17:54.160 --> 17:55.291
Jail, actually.

17:58.207 --> 18:01.036
But, uh,
since the ship's surgeon

18:01.167 --> 18:05.649
is apparently in Fort Johnston
tending soldiers,

18:05.780 --> 18:06.824
I'm afraid
you're stuck with me.

18:06.955 --> 18:08.391
God.

18:08.522 --> 18:10.524
We're not that desperate yet,
are we?

18:10.654 --> 18:11.568
Plucked from a jail.

18:13.266 --> 18:18.009
Imagine a governor driven
out of his palace

18:18.140 --> 18:20.186
and forced to flee
for his life.

18:20.273 --> 18:24.973
My husband hunted
by mobs of his own citizens.

18:25.104 --> 18:27.149
Marooned on this blasted ship

18:27.280 --> 18:28.672
when everything's going
to hell.

18:31.153 --> 18:33.286
I'm sorry we're not meeting
under better circumstances.

18:35.070 --> 18:38.291
But since
your husband did send for me...

18:38.421 --> 18:39.335
may I examine you?

18:41.163 --> 18:43.339
I can help. I promise.

18:53.784 --> 18:57.397
Have you been experiencing
any cramping, bleeding,

18:57.527 --> 18:58.659
intermittent pain in your back?

18:58.746 --> 19:00.835
No.

19:00.922 --> 19:03.142
[Claire] And how long
have you been ill?

19:03.229 --> 19:04.839
[sighs]
I've been vomiting all night

19:04.969 --> 19:07.711
and sweated through the sheets.

19:07.798 --> 19:11.193
Oh, I look positively ghastly.

19:11.324 --> 19:12.803
Perhaps I'll take
one of my tonics.

19:14.979 --> 19:17.852
Are you taking all of these
tonics at once, Mrs. Martin?

19:17.982 --> 19:19.810
[Mrs. Martin] One at breakfast,
another after luncheon.

19:19.941 --> 19:21.072
When the fever comes on,

19:21.203 --> 19:23.031
I use
the East Indian Chaulmoogra.

19:25.294 --> 19:26.817
[Claire]
Perhaps we can find you

19:26.948 --> 19:29.037
something more suitable.

19:29.168 --> 19:30.952
What if it's the tertian ague?

19:31.082 --> 19:33.041
[Claire sighs] It's not.

19:33.737 --> 19:36.087
Shouldn't you be
letting my blood?

19:36.218 --> 19:38.089
There's a fleam and bowl
over there.

19:38.220 --> 19:39.090
Unless...

19:40.701 --> 19:41.963
Oh, God, is it true?

19:42.093 --> 19:44.487
Are you the one who...

19:44.618 --> 19:47.925
who murdered her husband's
pregnant mistress

19:48.056 --> 19:49.536
and cut the baby
from her womb?

19:49.666 --> 19:51.364
It was you, wasn't it?

19:52.495 --> 19:55.063
She was not his mistress.

19:55.194 --> 19:56.586
And I didn't kill her.

19:56.717 --> 19:58.371
As for the rest...

19:58.501 --> 19:59.763
My husband doesn't know,
does he?

20:01.591 --> 20:03.202
I doubt it.

20:03.593 --> 20:05.029
How did you hear?

20:05.160 --> 20:07.684
Oh, you are quite notorious.

20:07.815 --> 20:09.382
The talk of the town.

20:10.296 --> 20:13.255
Of course, my husband has
no time for gossip

20:13.342 --> 20:15.257
and has no memory for names,
as I do.

20:17.041 --> 20:19.435
I've never known
a murderess before.

20:19.566 --> 20:21.611
I'm not a murderess.

20:21.698 --> 20:22.743
[Mrs. Martin]
Well, of course, you'd say so.

20:23.787 --> 20:25.746
You don't look depraved.

20:27.051 --> 20:29.271
Though I must say, you don't
look quite respectable either.

20:32.579 --> 20:33.841
It's ginger tea.

20:33.971 --> 20:35.016
It will help with the nausea.

20:37.148 --> 20:39.107
Not until you swear
you won't hurt my baby.

20:39.238 --> 20:41.022
You must swear it.

20:41.152 --> 20:44.982
Mrs. Martin... of course.

20:46.027 --> 20:48.421
Your husband brought me here
because I'm a healer.

20:48.508 --> 20:50.597
Harming someone would be
rather

20:50.727 --> 20:52.251
at cross purposes with that,
wouldn't it?

20:53.426 --> 20:55.384
You need fluids,

20:55.515 --> 20:56.951
for your own sake
and for the baby.

21:07.831 --> 21:10.181
Six children I've had,

21:10.312 --> 21:12.793
and I've lost three of them.

21:12.880 --> 21:14.708
I'd rather die
than lose another

21:14.838 --> 21:16.579
and break my husband's heart.

21:16.710 --> 21:17.972
He won't bear it.

21:18.102 --> 21:19.321
You're in no danger of that.

21:20.714 --> 21:22.629
I'd say you've eaten something

21:22.716 --> 21:23.586
that strongly disagrees
with you.

21:23.717 --> 21:24.457
That's all.

21:27.198 --> 21:28.896
I am a mother too.

21:31.594 --> 21:33.727
Let's settle you
into your cabin.

21:35.032 --> 21:37.034
And I'll go ask your husband

21:37.165 --> 21:39.254
to send for some
different medicine.

21:39.385 --> 21:40.429
Thank you.

21:43.302 --> 21:45.304
I won't say anything
about the charge if you don't.

21:51.658 --> 21:52.789
[Roger] Right.

21:53.224 --> 21:54.182
I'll see you later then.

21:55.749 --> 21:56.967
Bye.

21:57.098 --> 21:58.839
Whoa, what's all this?

22:00.101 --> 22:01.755
Gosh, there's enough food
in here to last three days.

22:03.670 --> 22:05.454
-Are you leaving me?
-[laughs]

22:05.585 --> 22:07.500
It's nothing. Snacks.

22:07.630 --> 22:09.415
And a farrier's hammer?

22:11.895 --> 22:14.594
You're going back to hand out
theological pamphlets.

22:14.724 --> 22:16.204
I didn't realize shoeing horses

22:16.291 --> 22:17.858
was part
of the job description.

22:17.945 --> 22:19.599
Ministering to animals now
as well?

22:23.994 --> 22:25.474
That's for Wendigo Donner,
isn't it?

22:27.650 --> 22:28.738
You're gonna try
to help him escape?

22:30.261 --> 22:31.654
Roger, what are you gonna do?

22:31.741 --> 22:33.482
Singlehandedly bust him out
of the army?

22:33.613 --> 22:35.441
Shh...

22:35.528 --> 22:37.878
You're not Steve McQueen
in The Great Escape.

22:38.008 --> 22:39.662
You're studying to be
a minister, for God's sake!

22:39.793 --> 22:41.185
I know that.

22:41.316 --> 22:43.710
I just...

22:43.840 --> 22:45.059
I thought maybe I would put in
a good word for him

22:45.189 --> 22:50.020
with the officers or...
something.

22:50.717 --> 22:52.501
-After what he did?
-Oh, but that's just it.

22:52.632 --> 22:53.720
According to Claire,
he didn't do anything.

22:53.850 --> 22:55.591
Right.

22:55.722 --> 22:58.638
He just stood by
and did nothing

22:58.768 --> 23:00.814
while my mother
was brutally attacked.

23:00.944 --> 23:04.426
And then he ran and hid
like a coward.

23:05.384 --> 23:06.515
What could he have done without
getting killed himself?

23:08.212 --> 23:09.300
You--you didn't see him, Bree.

23:09.431 --> 23:11.781
He--he's desperate, scared.

23:13.522 --> 23:15.959
He just wants to go home.

23:16.090 --> 23:18.353
He--he came back here
to help his fellow Indians,

23:18.440 --> 23:21.051
and everything went to shit.

23:21.182 --> 23:22.444
He was just trying to survive.

23:24.185 --> 23:25.578
When I came through the stones,

23:25.708 --> 23:27.318
I ended up on Bonnet's crew.

23:29.233 --> 23:30.583
I did what I had to.

23:32.411 --> 23:35.239
And I would've done anything
to find you.

23:35.370 --> 23:36.327
Anything.

23:36.458 --> 23:38.808
No. No.

23:38.895 --> 23:42.203
You would never, ever stand by

23:42.333 --> 23:43.596
and watch a woman be hurt,

23:43.726 --> 23:45.554
not like those men did

23:45.685 --> 23:47.426
in that tavern that night
when I came back,

23:47.556 --> 23:49.253
and not like Wendigo did
with Mama.

23:53.344 --> 23:56.304
I watched Bonnet...

23:56.435 --> 24:00.047
throw a child overboard
on that ship...

24:00.177 --> 24:01.962
[somber music plays]

24:02.092 --> 24:04.007
...and her mother
jump in after her.

24:04.094 --> 24:07.446
♪ ♪

24:07.576 --> 24:11.101
And though I was desperate
to intervene, I was frozen.

24:11.232 --> 24:12.929
I wanted to save them,
but I couldn't.

24:15.279 --> 24:18.500
I had to fight
every instinct in me,

24:18.631 --> 24:20.459
because I had to stay alive
to find you.

24:22.809 --> 24:25.246
I was outnumbered.

24:25.376 --> 24:27.683
Bonnet and his crew
would have killed me.

24:27.814 --> 24:29.468
And it was the same
for Wendigo.

24:31.470 --> 24:34.211
So how can I condemn him,

24:34.342 --> 24:37.127
as a man or as a minister?

24:37.301 --> 24:40.130
♪ ♪

24:41.567 --> 24:43.046
-Yeah, Roger...
-Bree.

24:55.319 --> 24:56.843
[Martin] We'll be ready,
Lieutenant Tate.

24:56.930 --> 24:59.889
Catch a steady wind.
Go up the Cape Fear a bit.

25:00.020 --> 25:03.676
Send raiding parties to shore,
and take back Fort Johnston.

25:03.806 --> 25:06.026
[Tate] With respect,
Your Excellency,

25:06.156 --> 25:08.071
if I may speak frankly,

25:08.158 --> 25:10.770
you can't mean to try
and attack in this fog.

25:10.857 --> 25:12.946
This is hardly the ship for it.

25:13.033 --> 25:15.296
-And the Captain says--
-We have to do something, Tate.

25:15.426 --> 25:17.864
Do you have any idea
what fate awaits me

25:17.994 --> 25:19.692
if I lose this wretched colony?

25:19.822 --> 25:21.215
The Redcoats will hang me

25:21.345 --> 25:22.999
before the goddamned rebels do.

25:23.130 --> 25:25.219
[Tate] We should have news
imminently.

25:25.349 --> 25:27.264
But the rebels are
far more numerous

25:27.351 --> 25:29.484
and better armed
than expected.

25:29.615 --> 25:32.226
And if they are holding
Fort Johnston, sir,

25:32.356 --> 25:35.229
then for your own sake
and the sake of your family,

25:35.316 --> 25:37.013
perhaps you might consider
sailing north.

25:39.276 --> 25:40.539
Forgive me...

25:42.932 --> 25:45.369
...but surely, your place
is here, Governor Martin.

25:45.500 --> 25:47.763
And yours, madam,
is in the surgeon's cabin,

25:47.894 --> 25:49.896
tending to my wife.

25:51.506 --> 25:52.986
Well, her condition
is much improved.

25:53.116 --> 25:56.642
I wanted to ask
if I could go fetch

25:56.772 --> 25:58.731
some additional supplies
in Wilmington for her.

25:58.861 --> 26:00.559
[Martin] Leave the ship?

26:00.689 --> 26:02.561
Do you have any idea
what it took to bring you here?

26:02.691 --> 26:04.214
Absolutely not.

26:05.302 --> 26:07.827
But your wife's continued
good health may depend on it.

26:07.957 --> 26:09.916
-[bell ringing]
-[Tate] Ahoy there.

26:10.046 --> 26:11.308
[person] We're coming aboard,
by your leave,

26:11.395 --> 26:12.571
in the name
of King George's Army.

26:12.701 --> 26:13.659
Please, Your Excellency,

26:13.789 --> 26:15.182
I...

26:15.312 --> 26:17.837
I just need to get
some extra supplies.

26:17.967 --> 26:19.926
Make a list,
and we'll send a messenger

26:20.056 --> 26:21.797
to collect whatever it is
you need before we set sail.

26:21.928 --> 26:23.625
Be quick about it.

26:23.756 --> 26:25.322
I don't imagine we'll be
in these waters much longer,

26:25.453 --> 26:26.323
no matter what happens.

26:28.282 --> 26:30.284
But when can I expect
to return to shore?

26:30.414 --> 26:32.460
It can't have escaped
your notice

26:32.591 --> 26:34.810
that my wife is with child.

26:34.941 --> 26:36.595
She'll require your assistance.

26:36.725 --> 26:37.857
You will remain on the ship

26:37.987 --> 26:39.423
for the duration
of our voyage.

26:39.554 --> 26:41.425
Consider it
your patriotic duty.

26:41.556 --> 26:43.166
Lieutenant Tate will convey
your letter to shore at once.

26:43.297 --> 26:44.428
Won't take long.

26:44.515 --> 26:45.865
What news, Major MacDonald?

26:48.084 --> 26:49.172
We've lost Fort Johnston, sir.

26:50.957 --> 26:51.653
It's certain, then?

26:55.265 --> 26:56.049
Fancy meeting you here.

26:58.138 --> 26:59.574
You know her?

26:59.705 --> 27:01.054
We've met.

27:01.184 --> 27:01.794
[MacDonald]
We most certainly have.

27:01.924 --> 27:03.360
Although last I heard,

27:03.491 --> 27:04.274
-you were--
-Fully intent

27:04.405 --> 27:06.450
on proving my innocence.

27:06.581 --> 27:08.235
Thank you, Major.

27:09.236 --> 27:11.499
[Martin] Well, before
you two become reacquainted,

27:11.630 --> 27:12.718
once you've given
your letter to Tate,

27:12.848 --> 27:14.023
could you fetch me something

27:14.110 --> 27:16.547
to ease the griping
in my stomach?

27:16.678 --> 27:18.114
A splash of brandy in it
couldn't hurt either.

27:22.815 --> 27:24.730
[indistinct chatter]

27:24.860 --> 27:27.036
Redcoats in the whorehouse.

27:27.167 --> 27:27.820
We might be able to get
something out of them.

27:27.950 --> 27:29.299
[Ian] Aye.

27:29.386 --> 27:30.910
They might know
where the sheriff is

27:30.997 --> 27:32.128
or where he's taken
Auntie Claire.

27:35.044 --> 27:37.873
[tense music plays]

27:38.047 --> 27:40.789
♪ ♪

27:46.186 --> 27:48.101
[MacDonald] We can rally
Loyalists, find more troops.

27:50.364 --> 27:51.365
Your servant, madam.

27:54.585 --> 27:56.152
I couldn't quite believe
my ears when I heard

27:56.239 --> 27:57.632
that you'd been arrested
for murder...

27:59.678 --> 28:01.288
...and- and that the girl's
father had accompanied you

28:01.418 --> 28:02.463
to Wilmington
with the express wish

28:02.593 --> 28:03.420
of seeing you hanged.

28:06.380 --> 28:08.512
He only wished to ensure
that I received a fair trial.

28:09.383 --> 28:11.472
Of course.

28:11.602 --> 28:14.257
If you're here
in such illustrious company,

28:14.344 --> 28:17.565
then I- I'm sure
that all must be in order.

28:17.696 --> 28:19.741
I assume this means that
your husband has seen sense

28:19.828 --> 28:24.354
and finally declared himself
for the Crown, Mrs. Fraser?

28:24.441 --> 28:26.617
You doubt this man's
allegiance, Major?

28:26.748 --> 28:28.141
Well, it's only that I assumed,

28:28.271 --> 28:30.186
since the good lady's husband

28:30.317 --> 28:32.145
resigned from his position
as Indian agent,

28:32.275 --> 28:34.495
among other things,
that they, uh...

28:34.625 --> 28:36.715
[chuckles]
How to put this politely...

28:36.845 --> 28:39.369
Your husband is James Fraser
of Fraser's Ridge?

28:40.544 --> 28:42.982
Yes. Yes, he is.

28:43.112 --> 28:44.897
[MacDonald] I do, of course,
very much hope

28:45.027 --> 28:46.637
that we can count on

28:46.768 --> 28:48.465
Mr. Fraser's support
in our endeavors,

28:48.552 --> 28:50.859
but there is some doubt,

28:50.990 --> 28:54.080
certainly,
as to the Frasers' integrity,

28:54.167 --> 28:55.342
-as you can see.
-How dare you.

28:55.472 --> 28:57.083
Could you excuse us, Major?

28:57.213 --> 28:58.388
Certainly, your Excellency.

28:58.519 --> 29:01.261
[tense music plays]

29:01.435 --> 29:04.177
♪ ♪

29:09.530 --> 29:10.749
Manipulative bastard.

29:26.939 --> 29:29.463
-[Tate] Mr. Thomas Christie?
-Yes?

29:29.593 --> 29:31.073
[Tate] A Mistress Claire Fraser

29:31.204 --> 29:33.032
requires your immediate
and most urgent assistance.

29:35.295 --> 29:38.385
She has assured us that you
are the man best able to help.

29:38.515 --> 29:40.996
But we require
your utmost discretion.

29:43.869 --> 29:45.348
You can procure
the necessary items,

29:45.435 --> 29:47.089
Mr. Christie?

29:47.176 --> 29:49.135
Items?

29:49.265 --> 29:51.137
Yes, of course.

29:51.267 --> 29:53.400
Of course, yes.

29:53.530 --> 29:55.968
For her patient
aboard HMS Cruizer.

29:57.839 --> 29:59.623
I am--I'm very happy
to be of service

29:59.754 --> 30:01.843
both to Mistress Fraser

30:01.930 --> 30:03.714
and to the Crown.

30:04.628 --> 30:05.629
And you will see
that she has enclosed

30:05.760 --> 30:07.544
a list of what is needed.

30:07.675 --> 30:09.372
Now, please bring everything
to the harbor

30:09.503 --> 30:11.157
at your earliest convenience.

30:11.287 --> 30:14.334
The ship, it's in the harbor?

30:14.421 --> 30:16.510
No, sir.

30:16.597 --> 30:18.729
But I will wait for you there
and convey whatever you bring,

30:18.817 --> 30:20.296
by boat, back to the ship.

30:20.427 --> 30:22.211
But please hurry.

30:22.342 --> 30:23.604
The Cruizerwill not be
at anchor for long.

30:35.616 --> 30:36.835
Vir meus...

30:51.980 --> 30:54.026
[Claire] Sheriff Tolliver
orchestrated my being here,

30:54.156 --> 30:56.550
so I assumed you knew
what my charge was

30:56.680 --> 30:58.030
and you were turning
a blind eye.

30:58.160 --> 30:59.727
Mistress Martin certainly did.

30:59.858 --> 31:01.381
There is that rather
insignificant matter

31:01.511 --> 31:03.035
of trying to govern
a royal colony

31:03.165 --> 31:04.732
from a goddamned
floating dungeon

31:04.863 --> 31:06.821
that's been occupying my time.

31:06.952 --> 31:09.302
The crew told me you were
a healer coming from the jail.

31:09.432 --> 31:11.130
I had neither the time
nor inclination

31:11.217 --> 31:13.741
to ask for any
of the unsavory details.

31:13.872 --> 31:15.482
[Claire] Exactly my point.

31:15.612 --> 31:18.224
You didn't care what I'd done
when you sent for me.

31:18.354 --> 31:20.269
You needed my help,
and I gave it.

31:20.400 --> 31:22.228
But a murderess,
it's unthinkable.

31:22.358 --> 31:26.710
I swear to you, I'm innocent.

31:26.841 --> 31:29.583
I found the young woman
in question already dead.

31:29.713 --> 31:30.801
But she was with child, so I--

31:30.932 --> 31:32.499
God in heaven,
it gets worse and worse.

31:32.629 --> 31:34.980
My poor wife, does she know
about all of this sorry tale?

31:35.110 --> 31:36.546
[Claire] You don't understand.

31:36.677 --> 31:40.637
I did what I could to save
that unborn child.

31:40.768 --> 31:43.510
And I will do everything I can
for your wife and your baby.

31:47.862 --> 31:50.647
Your wife told me

31:50.778 --> 31:53.172
that you'd both suffered
terrible losses.

31:53.694 --> 31:55.609
I know what it's like
to lose a child.

31:57.002 --> 31:58.612
There is no greater pain.

31:58.742 --> 32:00.701
It's unspeakable.

32:02.790 --> 32:05.924
My three beautiful boys.

32:08.361 --> 32:09.536
Sam, my youngest...

32:11.755 --> 32:14.019
Sometimes I think I glimpse him
running past.

32:16.499 --> 32:18.414
He was only eight years old.

32:18.893 --> 32:20.199
I'm so sorry.

32:22.331 --> 32:23.898
Yes, perhaps you should be,

32:23.985 --> 32:26.161
you and your husband both,

32:26.292 --> 32:29.817
because the only thing more
painful than losing my sons

32:29.904 --> 32:31.645
is knowing that
my three daughters will grow up

32:31.732 --> 32:33.386
in a world
that exists without them,

32:33.516 --> 32:35.605
without the men
they would have become,

32:35.736 --> 32:37.346
men who would have
protected them

32:37.433 --> 32:39.348
from those who choose violence
and bloodshed,

32:39.479 --> 32:41.960
chaos and anarchy
over law and order,

32:42.090 --> 32:44.527
those who would betray
their nation and choose war.

32:44.614 --> 32:48.749
But surely,
no one enters war willingly,

32:48.836 --> 32:51.099
no matter
one's personal convictions.

32:51.230 --> 32:53.232
And what exactly are you
and your husband's convictions,

32:53.362 --> 32:54.755
Mistress Fraser?

32:54.885 --> 32:58.411
To be charged with murder
is one thing,

32:58.541 --> 33:02.632
but to be suspected of treason
is quite another.

33:02.806 --> 33:05.592
♪ ♪

33:07.289 --> 33:09.117
That was disappointing.

33:09.248 --> 33:10.466
Maybe we'll have better luck
at the Old Bell.

33:14.340 --> 33:15.428
Mr. Fraser.

33:16.995 --> 33:18.213
What is it now, Mr. Christie?

33:18.344 --> 33:19.823
I know where
Mistress Fraser is.

33:19.954 --> 33:22.652
[dramatic music plays]

33:22.826 --> 33:24.741
♪ ♪

33:24.872 --> 33:26.787
Read it.

33:26.917 --> 33:28.354
She's on a ship, the Cruizer.

33:28.484 --> 33:30.617
She wants you to go to her.

33:30.747 --> 33:33.098
Vir meus,my husband.

33:33.185 --> 33:34.490
She wants you.

33:34.664 --> 33:37.406
♪ ♪

33:54.380 --> 33:55.381
[Claire] Lieutenant Tate.

33:55.511 --> 33:56.947
Back down below, please, madam.

33:57.035 --> 33:59.037
I just need some extra blankets
for Mrs. Martin.

33:59.167 --> 34:00.299
[bell rings]

34:03.389 --> 34:05.260
Boat, ahoy!

34:05.391 --> 34:08.132
[suspenseful music plays]

34:08.306 --> 34:11.049
♪ ♪

34:16.141 --> 34:17.141
Do you wish
to come aboard, sir?

34:17.272 --> 34:18.708
Aye, I do.

34:18.839 --> 34:20.536
By whose authority?

34:20.623 --> 34:22.408
[Jamie]
I am a former Indian agent

34:22.538 --> 34:23.713
in the governor's employ

34:23.844 --> 34:26.411
and an acquaintance...

34:26.542 --> 34:28.414
[dramatic music plays]

34:28.501 --> 34:30.110
...of Lord John Grey.

34:30.284 --> 34:33.071
♪ ♪

34:36.291 --> 34:37.900
Sassenach.

34:38.076 --> 34:40.817
♪ ♪

34:47.998 --> 34:49.956
[Tate] Excuse me.

34:50.088 --> 34:51.393
This is not permitted.

34:54.570 --> 34:56.050
I wish to speak
with the governor.

34:56.181 --> 34:58.052
I'm James Fraser
of Fraser's Ridge.

34:58.487 --> 35:00.185
I've come for my wife.

35:01.142 --> 35:03.449
I humbly ask that you allow me
to take her home.

35:03.579 --> 35:05.233
I regret to inform you, sir,

35:05.364 --> 35:08.715
that your wife is a prisoner
of the Crown,

35:08.845 --> 35:09.672
though perhaps
you were aware of this.

35:12.588 --> 35:15.156
It is true, is it not,
that you have declared

35:15.287 --> 35:17.550
martial law over the colony
of North Carolina?

35:18.420 --> 35:19.552
It is.

35:19.682 --> 35:21.075
Then you alone have control

35:21.206 --> 35:23.164
over the custody
of any prisoners.

35:24.513 --> 35:25.993
My wife is in your custody.

35:26.124 --> 35:27.777
You have the power
to release her.

35:27.908 --> 35:30.563
The crime of which
your wife stands accused

35:30.693 --> 35:32.347
is most heinous.

35:32.478 --> 35:33.392
There is no merit
to the charge.

35:39.049 --> 35:41.400
Surely,
having made her acquaintance,

35:41.487 --> 35:42.531
you'll have drawn
your own conclusions

35:42.662 --> 35:43.837
as to her character.

35:43.967 --> 35:45.143
And what conclusions
should I draw

35:45.230 --> 35:46.274
as to your character?

35:46.405 --> 35:48.189
Lord John Grey assured me

35:48.320 --> 35:49.886
that you were a man
to be counted upon,

35:50.017 --> 35:51.236
-but Major MacDonald said--
-[Jamie] Major MacDonald?

35:52.628 --> 35:54.239
My resignation as Indian agent?

35:56.458 --> 35:58.112
Surely, that is all behind us.

35:58.199 --> 36:00.158
Your unwillingness to elaborate
further on the matter

36:00.245 --> 36:01.724
speaks volumes, sir.

36:07.687 --> 36:10.080
I understand
Your Excellency's reservations.

36:13.083 --> 36:15.129
Perhaps some surety
may be offered.

36:15.260 --> 36:17.436
You have the impertinence
to try and bribe me?

36:17.566 --> 36:19.873
That was not my intent, sir.

36:20.003 --> 36:22.919
What I offer is a bond against
my wife's appearance in court.

36:23.006 --> 36:25.835
No, sir, I will not accept
a bond for your wife.

36:25.966 --> 36:27.576
I should hang the two of you
out of hand,

36:27.707 --> 36:29.012
have you swinging
from the yardarm.

36:29.143 --> 36:30.144
Your Excellency, please.

36:37.934 --> 36:39.545
I'm a reasonable man.

36:39.675 --> 36:41.155
I will offer you
a proposition.

36:41.286 --> 36:42.504
Return to the backcountry

36:42.635 --> 36:44.071
and gather such men
as you can.

36:44.202 --> 36:45.942
Then report to Major MacDonald

36:46.073 --> 36:48.554
and commit your troops
to his campaign.

36:49.424 --> 36:52.819
When I receive word from him
that you have, say, 200 men,

36:52.949 --> 36:55.648
then, sir, I will release
your wife to you.

36:55.735 --> 36:58.564
[tense music plays]

36:58.651 --> 37:01.044
♪ ♪

37:01.175 --> 37:02.307
Very well.

37:13.753 --> 37:14.884
Be still, a nighean.

37:15.015 --> 37:16.669
[somber music plays]

37:16.756 --> 37:18.540
Do not despair.

37:18.671 --> 37:20.107
I will see you
when the morning comes.

37:20.281 --> 37:23.023
♪ ♪

37:46.699 --> 37:49.441
[birds chirping]

37:53.575 --> 37:54.794
[grunts]

37:54.924 --> 37:55.534
[Roger] Excuse me, Miss.

37:57.449 --> 37:59.407
Do you have a moment to talk

37:59.538 --> 38:02.454
about someone who loves you
very much?

38:04.151 --> 38:06.066
I don't have time to talk
about God today.

38:06.196 --> 38:07.067
Thanks anyway.

38:09.417 --> 38:10.940
I was talking
about your husband.

38:12.681 --> 38:14.901
Do you have any time for him?

38:15.031 --> 38:16.424
Always.

38:18.470 --> 38:22.300
But he's been kinda busy
ministering to some soldiers.

38:22.430 --> 38:24.302
He's going to be ordained
himself, you see.

38:24.432 --> 38:26.129
-Oh?
-[Brianna] Mm.

38:26.260 --> 38:27.827
And how is that going for him?

38:30.220 --> 38:32.571
You'll be pleased to know
that he hasn't helped

38:32.701 --> 38:34.616
a certain conscript escape.

38:48.369 --> 38:50.284
But I do want to do something
for him, Bree.

38:53.243 --> 38:54.506
You listen to your instincts.

38:54.593 --> 38:55.811
I have to be able
to listen to mine.

38:57.204 --> 38:59.728
So I'm going to help Wendigo...

38:59.815 --> 39:01.469
by praying for him.

39:06.735 --> 39:08.781
Go on, then.

39:08.911 --> 39:10.870
Do it now
if it'll make you feel better.

39:23.056 --> 39:26.364
Lord, it is said
that God helps those

39:26.494 --> 39:28.148
who help themselves.

39:28.670 --> 39:30.890
I always found that confusing.

39:32.195 --> 39:35.547
Like those who help themselves
to the last slice of cake,

39:35.677 --> 39:36.765
or...

39:43.903 --> 39:47.950
Lord,
please help Wendigo Donner,

39:48.081 --> 39:51.389
or at least help him
to help himself.

39:51.519 --> 39:54.261
[soft music plays]

39:54.435 --> 39:57.612
♪ ♪

39:57.743 --> 39:59.266
You're going to be
a great minister.

39:59.440 --> 40:02.138
♪ ♪

40:05.490 --> 40:08.144
You'll never be able
to recruit enough men.

40:08.231 --> 40:10.451
I willna be recruitin' men.

40:10.582 --> 40:12.758
But I am goin' back
to that ship.

40:12.888 --> 40:14.063
[Ian] What will you do, Uncle?

40:14.194 --> 40:15.238
[dramatic music plays]

40:15.369 --> 40:16.805
Whatever I must.

40:16.979 --> 40:19.721
♪ ♪

40:21.680 --> 40:23.595
You should go back
to the Ridge.

40:23.725 --> 40:25.074
I dinna want ye involved.

40:25.205 --> 40:26.119
What d'ye mean?

40:26.249 --> 40:27.468
[Tom] Fraser.

40:30.384 --> 40:32.604
Tom.

40:32.734 --> 40:33.605
Is that a whisky in yer hand?

40:36.303 --> 40:38.827
I have wrestled with my demons.

40:40.176 --> 40:41.047
But it's you.

40:42.309 --> 40:43.571
It's always you.

40:45.399 --> 40:47.923
You are the answer
to my prayer.

40:48.054 --> 40:49.447
How much have ye had to drink?

40:50.883 --> 40:51.884
You must help me.

40:53.842 --> 40:54.669
I beg you.

40:56.454 --> 40:57.411
There is something I must do.

41:05.375 --> 41:07.682
Some air to clear yer heid.

41:07.813 --> 41:08.944
Ye're not accustomed to it.

41:09.075 --> 41:10.163
Whisky's addled yer wits.

41:22.349 --> 41:23.959
Over the years,
I've watched men come to you

41:24.090 --> 41:26.353
and ask for your help.

41:26.484 --> 41:27.485
You never turn them away.

41:28.877 --> 41:30.270
Will you refuse me now?

41:30.792 --> 41:33.273
Let me go to the Cruizer.

41:33.403 --> 41:34.970
Let me tell the governor
what I have done.

41:36.885 --> 41:38.539
Let me look Mistress Fraser
in the eye

41:38.670 --> 41:41.629
one last time and confess.

41:46.329 --> 41:49.463
On our wedding day,
I swore to Claire

41:49.594 --> 41:51.813
she'd have the protection
of my name,

41:51.944 --> 41:55.251
my clan, my family,

41:55.382 --> 41:56.992
and the protection of my...

41:57.123 --> 41:58.559
my body as well.

42:01.214 --> 42:02.302
I will honor that promise.

42:04.260 --> 42:05.523
I dinna need yer help.

42:08.003 --> 42:11.746
I believe that
in letting me go to her,

42:11.877 --> 42:14.140
you will honor that promise
just the same,

42:14.270 --> 42:15.663
just as you've honored
the promises made

42:15.794 --> 42:17.099
to those of us
who were at Ardsmuir.

42:21.974 --> 42:24.672
I have no name

42:24.803 --> 42:26.587
that carries any weight
in this world.

42:26.718 --> 42:28.110
[solemn music plays]

42:28.241 --> 42:29.634
A broken family.

42:29.808 --> 42:30.939
♪ ♪

42:31.070 --> 42:32.767
No clan of my own.

42:32.941 --> 42:35.857
♪ ♪

42:35.988 --> 42:37.772
Allow me to do this.

42:37.946 --> 42:40.688
♪ ♪

42:47.695 --> 42:49.741
I can say nothin'
to dissuade ye?

42:51.873 --> 42:53.571
No.

42:53.745 --> 42:56.486
♪ ♪

42:57.313 --> 43:00.012
[bell ringing]

43:11.240 --> 43:12.590
Send Claire back to me.

43:24.340 --> 43:27.648
That blackened day...

43:27.735 --> 43:30.129
Mistress Fraser told us

43:30.259 --> 43:32.610
what she would have said
about Malva at her funeral.

43:35.830 --> 43:37.353
I won't have a eulogy,

43:37.484 --> 43:39.529
and I don't know
what sort of burial awaits me.

43:39.660 --> 43:40.530
But...

43:43.316 --> 43:46.493
...I do wonder what you
might have said about me.

43:46.624 --> 43:48.016
-Tom...
-Please.

44:02.335 --> 44:03.162
I would say
that Thomas Christie

44:03.292 --> 44:04.685
was an honorable Scot...

44:07.079 --> 44:09.472
...a leader of men

44:09.603 --> 44:12.388
in his own way,

44:12.519 --> 44:15.304
though he didna ken
quite where to lead them.

44:20.135 --> 44:21.528
Stubborn as a damned mule...

44:23.748 --> 44:28.187
...but despite our differences,

44:28.274 --> 44:31.451
a man I respected

44:31.581 --> 44:33.845
and whose respect
I hope I had in return.

44:34.019 --> 44:36.717
♪ ♪

44:42.505 --> 44:43.681
[bell rings]

44:43.811 --> 44:45.378
[Tate] Boat, ahoy!

44:45.508 --> 44:48.207
[dramatic music plays]

44:48.381 --> 44:51.166
♪ ♪

45:02.612 --> 45:04.963
[Claire]
Jamie said he was coming back.

45:05.093 --> 45:06.138
[Tom]
You will see him presently.

45:06.268 --> 45:07.879
He awaits you in Wilmington.

45:08.009 --> 45:09.663
What the hell is going on?

45:09.794 --> 45:10.664
[door clicks]

45:16.061 --> 45:17.715
I've come to confess
to the murder of my daughter.

45:19.238 --> 45:20.848
No.

45:20.979 --> 45:22.328
No, you couldn't have.

45:22.458 --> 45:25.157
[Tom chuckles]
Still contrary, I see.

45:25.287 --> 45:27.507
-Are you insane?
-[Tom] It's the truth.

45:27.637 --> 45:29.161
I will swear to it
by the Holy Scriptures.

45:31.859 --> 45:34.383
I... [sighs]

45:36.516 --> 45:37.735
I don't understand.

45:40.694 --> 45:43.305
Do you remember once,

45:43.436 --> 45:44.567
you asked me
if I thought you a witch?

45:46.265 --> 45:48.006
You said
you didn't think I was one.

45:48.093 --> 45:51.139
No. But I have known them.

45:51.270 --> 45:52.575
The girl was one.
So was her mother.

45:55.491 --> 45:58.581
"The girl" was your daughter,
Malva.

46:01.976 --> 46:03.804
No daughter of mine.

46:04.805 --> 46:06.198
-Mr. Christie--
-[Tom] She was my brother's.

46:09.070 --> 46:10.202
Edgar.

46:13.683 --> 46:17.165
When the Rising came, I...

46:17.296 --> 46:20.212
declared for the Stuarts.

46:20.299 --> 46:22.257
He would have none of it,
saying it was folly. He...

46:23.911 --> 46:25.391
He begged me not to go.

46:28.046 --> 46:29.743
I asked him to look after
my wife and wee Allan.

46:29.830 --> 46:31.658
And he did.

46:32.877 --> 46:33.791
He certainly did.

46:36.924 --> 46:38.926
I see.

46:39.057 --> 46:40.319
[Tom] It wasn't his fault.

46:40.449 --> 46:43.104
Mona was a witch,

46:43.235 --> 46:44.497
an enchantress.

46:44.627 --> 46:46.107
And he succumbed to her.

46:48.501 --> 46:50.938
I see you don't believe me,
but it is the truth.

46:51.069 --> 46:53.071
More than once,
I caught her at it,

46:53.201 --> 46:56.465
working her charms
and staring at the stars,

46:56.596 --> 46:59.686
her hair flying loose,
mad in the wind.

47:02.080 --> 47:04.386
She had hair like mine,
didn't she?

47:04.517 --> 47:05.257
[Tom] Leave it.

47:10.218 --> 47:13.656
I tried to save her by prayer,
by God's grace.

47:13.787 --> 47:15.267
I could not.

47:16.094 --> 47:18.009
She was eventually hanged
for the murder of my brother.

47:19.880 --> 47:22.274
So you sent
for Allan and Malva.

47:22.404 --> 47:24.537
By the time she came to me,
Malva already had it,

47:24.667 --> 47:26.104
the same slyness, the charm,

47:26.234 --> 47:31.413
the same darkness of soul
as her mother.

47:32.675 --> 47:36.070
I tried to keep her from
working her wiles upon men.

47:36.201 --> 47:38.420
It was the curse of Lilith
that they had, both of them.

47:40.640 --> 47:42.076
She was with child.

47:42.207 --> 47:43.599
[Tom] I do not think it wrong

47:43.686 --> 47:46.733
to prevent yet another witch
from entering the world.

47:47.473 --> 47:49.083
You know
she tried to kill you?

47:49.214 --> 47:50.737
You and me both.

47:50.868 --> 47:52.521
You can't be certain of that.

47:52.652 --> 47:54.436
It was you who told me
that we suffered

47:54.567 --> 47:56.699
with the same illness
during the flux at the Ridge.

47:56.830 --> 47:58.658
You told her about
the invisible things,

47:58.788 --> 48:01.008
the--the germs.

48:01.139 --> 48:02.227
She confessed
when I caught her

48:02.357 --> 48:04.490
with the Sin-Eater's bones.

48:04.620 --> 48:05.970
She'd made a broth
to poison us with.

48:09.756 --> 48:11.149
Love charm.

48:12.977 --> 48:15.457
[sighs] She wanted Jamie.

48:15.588 --> 48:19.592
She lusted after wealth,
position.

48:21.376 --> 48:23.291
Or what she saw as freedom.

48:25.685 --> 48:28.253
Do you know who
the baby's father really was?

48:32.518 --> 48:34.433
I could not let her destroy
so many lives,

48:34.563 --> 48:35.347
for she was a witch.

48:35.477 --> 48:36.609
Make no mistake.

48:36.739 --> 48:37.653
She would have killed someone

48:37.740 --> 48:39.307
before she finished.

48:40.395 --> 48:42.528
So you decided to bear
that cross for her?

48:44.573 --> 48:45.879
She was not born of my loins,

48:45.966 --> 48:48.403
and yet she was my daughter,

48:48.534 --> 48:50.231
my blood.

48:50.362 --> 48:51.624
I am responsible.

48:55.802 --> 48:57.673
[whispering]
I don't believe you, Tom.

49:01.547 --> 49:02.896
[soft music plays]

49:03.027 --> 49:07.161
I have waited all my life

49:07.248 --> 49:08.249
in search of...

49:08.380 --> 49:12.819
no, in hope of a thing

49:12.950 --> 49:15.126
I could not name
but I knew must exist.

49:15.213 --> 49:18.390
♪ ♪

49:18.520 --> 49:22.089
I was convinced
it was God I sought,

49:22.220 --> 49:25.484
but the love of God alone
could not sustain me.

49:25.571 --> 49:26.528
No.

49:28.835 --> 49:30.750
Now I know

49:30.837 --> 49:32.099
that I...

49:34.710 --> 49:36.625
...I love you.

49:36.799 --> 49:39.541
♪ ♪

49:50.639 --> 49:51.466
Here, now...

49:54.295 --> 49:56.863
I have written down
my confession.

50:00.562 --> 50:03.739
I have sworn
that I killed my daughter

50:03.870 --> 50:06.264
for the shame she had brought
on me by her wantonness.

50:10.224 --> 50:12.139
-No.
-I have written another copy

50:12.270 --> 50:14.228
of this confession
and have already left it

50:14.359 --> 50:15.751
with the newspaper
in Wilmington.

50:17.927 --> 50:19.929
They will publish it,
and you will go free.

50:23.716 --> 50:27.328
I have yearned always for love,

50:27.459 --> 50:30.201
given and returned.

50:30.331 --> 50:34.074
I've spent my life
in the attempt to give my love

50:34.205 --> 50:35.858
to those
who are not worthy of it.

50:38.644 --> 50:39.906
Allow me this...

50:43.214 --> 50:47.087
...to give my life
for the sake of one who is.

50:47.174 --> 50:50.221
♪ ♪

50:50.308 --> 50:53.659
Your life has value.

50:54.616 --> 50:56.357
You can't throw it away
like this.

50:59.273 --> 51:00.318
I know that.

51:07.977 --> 51:10.850
If I did not,
then this would not matter.

51:12.156 --> 51:13.722
Go to your husband.

51:17.683 --> 51:19.206
There must be something
we can do.

51:19.337 --> 51:21.252
Lieutenant Tate...

51:21.339 --> 51:22.557
I'm ready now.

51:22.731 --> 51:25.473
♪ ♪

52:24.750 --> 52:26.491
Did you make Tom confess?

52:29.015 --> 52:29.798
No.

52:31.713 --> 52:34.368
No, he--he told me
what he intended to do,

52:34.499 --> 52:35.717
and I told him bide.

52:39.199 --> 52:41.636
I did tell him
that I'd have another go

52:41.767 --> 52:43.769
at trying to get you back,
but he--he insisted.

52:46.989 --> 52:48.817
So you don't think
he did it either?

52:51.603 --> 52:53.561
He only said he stayed silent
while there was any chance

52:53.692 --> 52:55.737
of you bein' tried
and acquitted,

52:55.868 --> 52:56.999
but...

53:00.394 --> 53:02.091
...had you ever been
in any urgent danger,

53:02.222 --> 53:04.355
he'd have spoken up at once.

53:04.485 --> 53:07.575
That's why he insisted on
coming wi' us to Wilmington.

53:07.706 --> 53:09.969
But that doesn't make
any sense.

53:11.013 --> 53:12.754
Why didn't he speak up
in front of Brown?

53:13.929 --> 53:16.149
I wondered if it was Brown

53:16.236 --> 53:17.455
who killed Malva himself,

53:17.585 --> 53:20.458
but... lookin' for revenge.

53:21.633 --> 53:22.764
Maybe.

53:26.899 --> 53:28.683
I just can't believe
it was Tom.

53:28.814 --> 53:31.208
Tell me he didn't make
that confession for me.

53:35.560 --> 53:38.171
[soft music plays]

53:38.302 --> 53:39.955
He loves you.

53:40.042 --> 53:41.218
♪ ♪

53:41.348 --> 53:42.915
It's plain to see, Sassenach.

53:43.089 --> 53:45.570
♪ ♪

53:45.700 --> 53:48.790
I'd have done the same,

53:48.921 --> 53:53.186
counted my life well lost
if it saved you.

53:53.360 --> 53:56.363
♪ ♪

53:56.494 --> 53:59.148
But how can I let him
sacrifice himself for me?

54:02.239 --> 54:04.371
They're going to hang him,
Jamie.

54:04.502 --> 54:05.677
[Jamie]
If he feels the same as me,

54:05.807 --> 54:08.810
then you've done
no wrong to him

54:08.941 --> 54:11.291
to take your life
from his hand.

54:13.250 --> 54:14.468
It's what he wanted.

54:19.604 --> 54:21.649
Rest now, mo chridhe.

54:21.823 --> 54:24.609
♪ ♪

54:59.208 --> 55:01.472
[door clicking]

55:01.602 --> 55:04.344
[indistinct chatter]

55:04.518 --> 55:07.260
♪ ♪

55:25.887 --> 55:26.975
[Jamie] I saw your horse.

55:27.106 --> 55:28.020
[dramatic music plays]

55:28.107 --> 55:30.196
I'd know him anywhere.

55:30.327 --> 55:33.025
Stared at his arse
for 200 miles.

55:33.199 --> 55:35.984
♪ ♪

55:36.942 --> 55:39.553
So...

55:39.684 --> 55:41.338
you didn't fancy a trip

55:41.468 --> 55:45.733
back to bonnie Scotland then,
eh, Mr. Fraser?

55:45.820 --> 55:48.562
♪ ♪

55:51.565 --> 55:52.479
No.

55:57.702 --> 55:59.312
No, thank ye.

55:59.399 --> 56:01.401
I'd prefer to wait until after.

56:04.883 --> 56:06.363
"After"?

56:08.887 --> 56:10.105
Come now.

56:11.933 --> 56:15.807
You harm a hair on my head,

56:15.937 --> 56:18.549
you know my kin
will hunt you down,

56:18.679 --> 56:21.813
kill everyone you hold dear.

56:21.943 --> 56:23.641
I've spared them the trouble.

56:23.771 --> 56:26.208
[tense music plays]

56:26.383 --> 56:27.253
♪ ♪

56:27.384 --> 56:30.691
By now, my nephew,

56:30.822 --> 56:33.738
the Indian ye tormented,

56:33.868 --> 56:35.609
will be payin' yer men
a wee visit.

56:37.611 --> 56:39.352
His Cherokee acquaintances
will be giving him

56:39.483 --> 56:40.788
a helping hand too.

56:40.962 --> 56:43.748
♪ ♪

56:57.501 --> 56:58.937
We'll have no more trouble
from them.

57:06.945 --> 57:08.468
You're a good man.

57:11.123 --> 57:14.126
A moral man.

57:14.256 --> 57:15.910
I'm also a violent man.

57:18.435 --> 57:19.914
Any goodness
that prevails in me

57:20.045 --> 57:21.307
is because of my wife.

57:24.266 --> 57:26.225
You tried to take her from me.

57:28.096 --> 57:29.358
You won't kill me.

57:32.144 --> 57:33.624
Not in cold blood.

57:36.453 --> 57:38.716
You wouldn't dare.

57:38.846 --> 57:42.371
Make your peace with the Lord
if you must...

57:42.502 --> 57:43.677
Mr. Brown.

57:43.808 --> 57:46.593
[dramatic music plays]

57:46.767 --> 57:49.074
♪ ♪

58:01.260 --> 58:04.002
[solemn music plays]

58:04.176 --> 58:06.918
♪ ♪
